                              <td valign="top" style="font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color:#333333; font-size:12px;">
                                <p align="justify">During the past few years, the stock markets have been like a rollercoaster ride. While we have seen some good times in the past, we cannot ignore the fact that the markets have also been on shaky grounds. We know how to handle the good periods, with joy and elation. But what do you do when anxiety and panic sets in, during those volatile years?</p>

                                <p align="justify">There is no ignoring the fact that volatility of the markets does have a serious impact on your financial health. This impact increases especially when the goal that you have invested for is a long term goal, like your retirement.</p>
                                
                                <p align="justify">Though volatile markets rarely last for long stretches of time, it is known to be a frequent occurrence. So what can you do to protect your retirement plans?</p>
                                
                                <p align="justify"><strong>Understand  your timeframe:</strong> If your retirement portfolio is facing a risk because of the volatility of the market, the first thing you need to understand is the time frame of realizing that goal.</p>
                                
                                <p align="justify">If you have more than 10 years to reach your retirement, you still have time to balance the results from your financial plan.</p>
                                
                                <p align="justify">However, if you are about to hit your retirement within the next two years, you first need to assess the risks involved in your plan. If the losses are limited and only a smaller percentage of your total investment, then you do not have to worry.  But if there are significant losses involved, it maybe in your best interest to rework on your investment options, with the help of your financial planner.</p>
                                
                                <p align="justify"><strong>Progressive allocation is the key:</strong> Retirement is not a onetime event, but a rather a phase in oneâ€™s life. So, while you are creating a corpus for your retirement, remember that you need a continuous flow of money year on year. In such cases its best to follow progressive allocations of resources.</p>
                                
                                <p align="justify">As a part of this method, funds that you require immediately i.e. over the next one year are invested conservatively in assets with minimum risk. As the time period of to meet your goal increases, your investments can be placed in comparatively more aggressive assets classes. Hence, funds that you need after 7-8 years can be invested in assets which can provide highest gains. Every year, this cycle can continue to ensure that your immediate requirements are always stable.</p> 
                                
                                <p align="justify">By following this approach, you can not only protect yourself from downside but also optimize your returns.</p>
                                <p align="justify"><strong>Continue  to save and invest:</strong> Many believe that it is a futile idea to continue saving and investing for the future, especially when the present times are tough. Instead of backing out on your investments, assess the risk involved first. Investing in newer options during this times also allows you to save more, for long term goals like retirement, without spending too much of your resources.  If you are unsure of investing in stocks, you can choose to invest in government bonds that tend to be more stable, even during tough times.</p>
                                
